1
00:00:01,020 --> 00:00:02,340
Hi everyone.

2
00:00:02,700 --> 00:00:07,100
I've finished work on tuning the lab power supply.

3
00:00:08,180 --> 00:00:11,520
And now before you is its schematic diagram.

4
00:00:11,840 --> 00:00:16,440
The scheme came out big and fits on two A4 sheets.

5
00:00:17,340 --> 00:00:23,000
It's already located in the folder at the address on Yandex.Disk you know.

6
00:00:23,160 --> 00:00:25,900
The address will also be duplicated in the video description.

7
00:00:25,900 --> 00:00:40,040
In the course of working on this build, some features came up that were reflected in practice in changes to the device's schematic diagram.

8
00:00:41,600 --> 00:00:50,760
The most radical change in the build, you could say, happened specifically in the power module.

9
00:00:50,880 --> 00:00:53,060
The power switches were replaced.

10
00:00:53,060 --> 00:01:03,160
Originally I planned to use power switches in TO-247 case, brand IRFP-064N.

11
00:01:03,820 --> 00:01:23,260
But in the course of testing it turned out that these HCPL3120 drivers, which have a max pulse current of 2 A, aren't able to saturate the gate capacitance of these transistors qualitatively.

12
00:01:24,860 --> 00:01:29,900
And so I had two solutions for this problem.

13
00:01:30,380 --> 00:01:43,060
Either replace the transistors, or use current amplifiers after the drivers on complementary pairs of bipolar transistors.

14
00:01:43,060 --> 00:01:45,960
Done on this kind of scheme.

15
00:01:46,340 --> 00:01:52,540
Our driver, a chosen resistance, then complementary pairs go.

16
00:01:52,620 --> 00:02:00,340
For example this KT-972, KT-973, or KT-805 and KT-835.

17
00:02:01,160 --> 00:02:08,220
Well, and further everything by scheme — limiting resistor, diodes, zeners, and power switch.

18
00:02:08,220 --> 00:02:11,180
But I didn't go down this path.

19
00:02:11,740 --> 00:02:18,200
It's a very good path for controlling heavy gates.

20
00:02:18,620 --> 00:02:29,020
I didn't take it for one reason — because of the mounting density on my board, installing 8 switches wasn't possible anymore.

21
00:02:29,140 --> 00:02:30,220
Simply no space.

22
00:02:30,800 --> 00:02:38,720
Because of this I stopped on transistors of brand IRFZ48N.

23
00:02:39,720 --> 00:02:57,700
These transistors come in TO-220 case — such a case is much smaller, but nevertheless they handle the set task excellently and don't spoil the build at all.

24
00:02:57,700 --> 00:03:06,000
And also their feature is that the gate capacitance is much smaller.

25
00:03:06,180 --> 00:03:14,580
If you take the IRFP064N, there's 4000 pF, and on these — 2500 pF.

26
00:03:15,200 --> 00:03:22,300
And in the course of testing I found this driver can work with capacitance up to 2800 pF.

27
00:03:26,470 --> 00:03:30,510
These switches are placed on the heat sink.

28
00:03:31,150 --> 00:03:37,190
Everything the same as I showed in the video — all the same operations on the power module.

29
00:03:38,270 --> 00:03:46,890
The next moment where changes were made — this is in the power transformer.

30
00:03:47,890 --> 00:04:00,030
You can notice that I changed the turn count of the primary winding, reduced it to 4-7, and I use only 7 leads from the transformer.

31
00:04:00,170 --> 00:04:05,890
Originally 11 turns were wound in 3 layers of the secondary winding.

32
00:04:05,890 --> 00:04:27,030
But since at the 11th lead and subsequent the voltage already too far exceeded the task I set — 1000 volts — I decided to unwind those turns, and as a total I got rid of one layer on the pulse transformer.

33
00:04:28,030 --> 00:04:36,310
Now this build looks like this — nothing changed, only one layer removed, and you see 4 turns.

34
00:04:37,370 --> 00:04:44,190
It's also all mounted and the leads from the transformer are connected to the distribution switch.

35
00:04:45,110 --> 00:04:51,470
These switches come with such metal parts in the kit.

36
00:04:51,470 --> 00:04:53,930
You can see I modified it slightly here.

37
00:04:54,790 --> 00:05:16,310
They sit in these holes and have such a tab that, when it moves, abuts the metal tab of the limiter, and the switch can't be switched further.

38
00:05:16,530 --> 00:05:21,450
This way we determine the final number of its switchings.

39
00:05:21,470 --> 00:05:28,790
Next we tuned the chain responsible for the work of the current protection.

40
00:05:29,010 --> 00:05:33,930
This is this resistance and the limiting resistance.

41
00:05:34,170 --> 00:05:37,990
And here is the chain coming from the current sensor.

42
00:05:38,830 --> 00:05:39,190
Bridge.

43
00:05:40,690 --> 00:05:42,810
Ratings are now marked.

44
00:05:43,530 --> 00:06:06,850
In previous experiments I used as resistance variable resistors of this brand, but it turned out they're very low-power and at current sensor work the contacts simply burn on the track.

45
00:06:07,850 --> 00:06:18,260
Although the current isn't too big, but nevertheless these transistors don't handle the set task and it was decided to replace them.

46
00:06:19,270 --> 00:06:26,670
I found resistors of brand PPB1A — the brand I also indicated.

47
00:06:27,730 --> 00:06:33,330
The resistance I installed is 100 Ohm.

48
00:06:33,330 --> 00:06:39,310
But here resistors with resistance from 47 Ohm will work well.

49
00:06:40,490 --> 00:06:48,450
I would've installed such a 47 Ohm resistance, but it isn't available at the suppliers.

50
00:06:48,950 --> 00:06:52,750
These resistors are for some reason in short supply.

51
00:06:53,670 --> 00:06:57,570
They're made from nichrome wire.

52
00:06:58,570 --> 00:07:02,010
The power rating of these resistors is fairly high.

53
00:07:02,750 --> 00:07:14,810
The contact surfaces are also made very qualitatively — these tabs, which prevents their failure — ceramic case.

54
00:07:16,250 --> 00:07:21,770
So I advise using exactly such variable resistors.

55
00:07:22,530 --> 00:07:24,770
To avoid work failures.

56
00:07:25,290 --> 00:07:27,410
What else can I say here.

57
00:07:28,770 --> 00:07:41,270
This resistance going to the common of the chip is responsible for the final trip current of the protection.

58
00:07:41,770 --> 00:07:46,690
In my case this resistance is 2.7 Ohm.

59
00:07:46,690 --> 00:07:54,590
And here you can put somewhere up to 5 Ohm — this will be a different point.

60
00:07:55,010 --> 00:08:04,490
Earlier I tuned the consumption point to 20 A, but at 2.7 Ohm this is 32 A.

61
00:08:05,110 --> 00:08:15,370
The trip point turns out — and these switches handle such a short-circuit load excellently.

62
00:08:17,210 --> 00:08:29,610
Moving on to the chains responsible for control of stopping chip generation.

63
00:08:31,490 --> 00:08:44,470
This chain is made on a divider from resistors of ratings 1.3 kOhm and 330 Ohm.

64
00:08:45,370 --> 00:08:49,890
From them a potential of about 2.5 V forms.

65
00:08:51,010 --> 00:09:04,210
And we can notice that this potential goes through the generation-off switch — it's presented here in my build.

66
00:09:04,330 --> 00:09:13,110
Further goes a push button with normally closed contacts — namely closed, not open.

67
00:09:13,110 --> 00:09:24,490
And visible that I marked a coaxial cable here, whose shield is mandatorily connected to the common with the generator.

68
00:09:25,450 --> 00:09:41,170
If you don't do this, then this piece of wire from the switch, button, and the marked point E here — here it is, the input to pin 9 — it'll form a kind of antenna.

69
00:09:41,170 --> 00:09:54,050
And during work, interference induced on it from primary winding work will be significant, which will lead to false trips of the current protection.

70
00:09:54,050 --> 00:10:02,810
Since pin 9 of the UC3825N chip is quite sensitive.

71
00:10:03,370 --> 00:10:08,530
Its work is from 0.9 to 1.3 volts.

72
00:10:08,770 --> 00:10:12,670
1.3 volts is already a full generation cutoff.

73
00:10:12,670 --> 00:10:16,870
So I advise doing this without fail.

74
00:10:17,790 --> 00:10:27,140
Let's examine in more detail what this chain of switch and button can be used for.

75
00:10:28,710 --> 00:10:42,060
First, on switch closure we switch our chip to standby mode — supply of control pulses from pins 14 and 11 of UC3825N stops.

76
00:10:43,390 --> 00:10:51,210
This is very convenient — no need to disconnect power to the whole lab block.

77
00:10:52,210 --> 00:11:21,350
Also, if we want to test a circuit connected after the lab power supply at its output, and we're not sure how it'll react to a long turn-on, we briefly press this button with normally closed contacts — the contacts open and the chip switches back to operating mode.

78
00:11:22,650 --> 00:11:31,650
We determine how the subsequent device behaves, make conclusions, and introduce corrections in the lab power supply control.

79
00:11:32,650 --> 00:11:59,130
Also, with this button it's very convenient to set the voltage potential — connect a voltmeter to the power supply output, set the point at the desired voltage with the switch, and set the voltage protection trip point.

80
00:11:59,130 --> 00:12:08,550
Press the button and fix the voltage potential that comes out at the output.

81
00:12:09,110 --> 00:12:11,210
Functional and convenient.

82
00:12:11,270 --> 00:12:24,250
Now let's examine the work of the system responsible for smooth regulation of voltage at the power supply output and setting its final point.

83
00:12:24,250 --> 00:12:30,330
This system required an additional galvanically isolated power source.

84
00:12:30,790 --> 00:12:36,110
I schematically marked it as 4 turns from the DC-DC converter.

85
00:12:36,110 --> 00:12:46,130
Technically I did it — see the DC-DC converters, here I added these 4 turns.

86
00:12:46,950 --> 00:12:51,010
And further they go to the subsequent scheme.

87
00:12:52,170 --> 00:12:57,010
This is a half-wave rectifier scheme.

88
00:12:58,190 --> 00:13:03,450
Here you get a potential of about 9 volts.

89
00:13:03,450 --> 00:13:07,790
There's a limiting zener of 8.2 volts.

90
00:13:08,330 --> 00:13:12,450
Further goes a regulator in a small case — 78L05.

91
00:13:13,450 --> 00:13:27,450
The currents consumed here are quite small, because in the end this chain only works to trigger the LED in the PC817 opto-coupler.

92
00:13:27,450 --> 00:13:38,710
Here you see points C, D — and in the scheme outputs also go to these points C, D.

93
00:13:39,590 --> 00:13:55,450
As a tracking element for the potential it was decided to use the circuit solution that has recommended itself well — namely the TL431 controllable zener.

94
00:13:56,810 --> 00:14:14,550
Potential from the resistor divider is supplied to its pin 1, and when this potential's threshold reaches 2.5 volts, it's compared with the reference voltage of 2.5 volts and the chip trips.

95
00:14:14,990 --> 00:14:20,090
On tripping we accordingly light the LED in the opto-coupler.

96
00:14:21,090 --> 00:14:28,570
Now let's dwell on this resistor divider in more detail.

97
00:14:29,010 --> 00:14:32,510
2 watt resistors must be placed here.

98
00:14:32,770 --> 00:14:42,050
They're not only a divider but also discharge these capacitances at the power supply output.

99
00:14:42,050 --> 00:14:46,330
These also work for us.

100
00:14:46,490 --> 00:15:05,230
This is also done for safety, so the voltage potential after power supply shutoff doesn't remain on the output terminals — with this I introduced a safety system on capacitor discharge.

101
00:15:06,990 --> 00:15:12,970
The resistance connecting to minus is 4.7 kOhm.

102
00:15:13,310 --> 00:15:25,490
Such a rating wasn't chosen by accident — at such a rating the maximum voltage that may be on the output terminals is 1050 volts.

103
00:15:25,490 --> 00:15:29,010
Further goes the variable resistance.

104
00:15:29,610 --> 00:15:32,310
I have a 15 kOhm there.

105
00:15:33,270 --> 00:15:46,870
Resistor brand PP340 — also wire-wound, this resistance, from nichrome.

106
00:15:47,490 --> 00:15:56,710
Because all other resistances will work here only for some time and fail.

107
00:15:57,170 --> 00:16:05,650
Although the currents are small, the reliability of other variable resistors leaves much to be desired.

108
00:16:06,650 --> 00:16:11,870
And the main limiting resistance is 2.2 MOhm.

109
00:16:12,190 --> 00:16:18,810
Such a divider lets us qualitatively track the voltage point at the output.

110
00:16:19,550 --> 00:16:31,630
You can also notice that parallel to the 2.2 MOhm one more resistance of 2.2 MOhm is connected, only through a switch.

111
00:16:31,630 --> 00:16:47,710
On closure of this switch the rating falls and the range of variable output voltage point on the power supply shifts to the lower side.

112
00:16:47,710 --> 00:17:02,010
In my case the regulation with the switch closed is from 100 to 500 volts, and with it open — from 300 to 1050 volts.

113
00:17:02,790 --> 00:17:15,330
You can pick any ratings for the desired voltage of your build here, but you'll have to pick these chains in practice.

114
00:17:15,330 --> 00:17:20,930
And now let's stop on the power chain of the whole scheme.

115
00:17:21,590 --> 00:17:27,710
The power chain starts with a battery, removable terminals.

116
00:17:29,070 --> 00:17:41,750
Then, according to the block scheme I showed earlier, at the input we have a 12 V 40 A relay with a diode.

117
00:17:41,750 --> 00:17:50,970
This diode makes the relay trip only at correct polarity of battery connection.

118
00:17:51,470 --> 00:17:59,430
With this we prevent the system from failing on a power-input reversal.

119
00:18:00,690 --> 00:18:06,410
A kind of protection that won't let the whole subsequent scheme get killed.

120
00:18:07,410 --> 00:18:18,630
Further, at the input we have electrolytic capacitors of 4700 µF 25 V, connected in series — 2 pieces.

121
00:18:19,070 --> 00:18:20,410
Then comes the choke.

122
00:18:21,250 --> 00:18:27,510
After that also 2 electrolytic capacitors of 4700 µF 25 V.

123
00:18:28,210 --> 00:18:34,910
And parallel to them is a 2.2 µF 400 V capacitor.

124
00:18:36,030 --> 00:18:45,510
This is what the 2.2 µF 400 V capacitor looks like.

125
00:18:45,630 --> 00:18:46,890
Quite massive.

126
00:18:47,010 --> 00:18:53,650
I advise not to save on this film capacitor, not to take it for lower voltage.

127
00:18:54,170 --> 00:18:59,910
The voltage of this capacitor ultimately determines its dimensions.

128
00:19:00,470 --> 00:19:12,230
And this capacitance participates in the work of the power module, in the primary dump of potential on the switches.

129
00:19:13,030 --> 00:19:19,410
That is, it accelerates the work in pulses of the power module.

130
00:19:20,590 --> 00:19:29,310
Also these capacitors, electrolytes connected in series — this also isn't a chance solution.

131
00:19:29,830 --> 00:19:36,450
Because these capacitors at peak loads will heat up in the course of work.

132
00:19:36,550 --> 00:19:43,750
And we need to distribute the load that falls on them across 4 capacitors.

133
00:19:44,030 --> 00:19:47,710
The filter choke also takes part in this work.

134
00:19:47,710 --> 00:19:57,110
And if we look at the scheme, then the DC-DC converter that ultimately powers the whole scheme is connected, on our side.

135
00:19:57,370 --> 00:19:59,970
Power on plus is supplied before the choke.

136
00:20:00,970 --> 00:20:05,750
The choke is a filter from the power module's work.

137
00:20:05,850 --> 00:20:07,270
See points A and B.

138
00:20:08,130 --> 00:20:14,510
And these are the points where A and B are supplied to the power module.

139
00:20:15,510 --> 00:20:20,530
In iron this looks as follows.

140
00:20:21,610 --> 00:20:22,810
Now let's examine.

141
00:20:24,110 --> 00:20:28,810
Everything's already ready and packed.

142
00:20:29,370 --> 00:20:31,350
Here at the input we have the relay.

143
00:20:32,350 --> 00:20:40,490
Next, the wire coming from the relay on plus comes to us.

144
00:20:40,490 --> 00:20:44,590
Here they are — capacitors located in series.

145
00:20:45,430 --> 00:20:46,190
Two pieces.

146
00:20:48,130 --> 00:20:49,790
Next comes the choke.

147
00:20:50,770 --> 00:20:54,610
And two more electrolytic capacitors.

148
00:20:54,810 --> 00:20:58,390
And further parallel stands the 2.2 µF capacitor.

149
00:20:59,930 --> 00:21:05,490
Here are two metal pieces with M3 thread.

150
00:21:06,070 --> 00:21:09,270
Here I soldered nuts.

151
00:21:10,490 --> 00:21:15,590
So that when I assemble this build.

152
00:21:16,070 --> 00:21:18,610
See contacts in the form of forks.

153
00:21:19,290 --> 00:21:26,830
They descend, engaging with these contact pads.

154
00:21:27,050 --> 00:21:32,230
And when the cover is closed, these screws tighten.

155
00:21:32,390 --> 00:21:37,090
That way a quality contact is made.

156
00:21:38,850 --> 00:21:41,850
By this choke.

157
00:21:43,010 --> 00:21:49,670
Its core dimensions are shown on the drawing.

158
00:21:50,390 --> 00:21:51,610
Here it is, this core.

159
00:21:51,730 --> 00:21:55,230
I marked it as F in a circle.

160
00:21:55,610 --> 00:21:58,830
And here F with an arrow indicates.

161
00:22:00,170 --> 00:22:05,010
Core dimensions are 28.5 mm in length.

162
00:22:05,010 --> 00:22:09,340
13 mm inner diameter.

163
00:22:10,270 --> 00:22:12,990
And wall width 6.5 mm.

164
00:22:13,490 --> 00:22:15,930
By outer it's 26 mm.

165
00:22:16,330 --> 00:22:17,550
Such a barrel.

166
00:22:18,410 --> 00:22:21,290
You can naturally use others.

167
00:22:21,830 --> 00:22:31,550
Simply for the dimensions of the box that I originally chose, exactly these cores fit me.

168
00:22:32,110 --> 00:22:37,170
Which have big dimensions in length.

169
00:22:41,030 --> 00:22:44,030
What else can you see here.

170
00:22:45,450 --> 00:22:47,150
Here is this switch.

171
00:22:48,990 --> 00:22:52,790
Which does range regulation.

172
00:22:53,410 --> 00:22:57,250
This is the resistance switch.

173
00:22:58,270 --> 00:23:04,130
Which sets the voltage protection trip point.

174
00:23:05,390 --> 00:23:06,990
Here it's presented.

175
00:23:07,590 --> 00:23:11,130
This is the current protection regulation resistance.

176
00:23:12,070 --> 00:23:14,770
And this is a variable resistance.

177
00:23:15,170 --> 00:23:20,450
This is the smooth regulation of output voltage.

178
00:23:21,570 --> 00:23:25,650
Effectively it regulates the duration of control pulses.

179
00:23:25,650 --> 00:23:33,990
And then the chip itself, based on all settings, sets the final duration of the control pulse.

180
00:23:35,990 --> 00:23:37,030
Further.

181
00:23:38,110 --> 00:23:39,570
The diode bridge.

182
00:23:40,050 --> 00:23:45,730
I marked here that it consists of fast diodes of brand MUR-860.

183
00:23:47,130 --> 00:23:54,050
And drew graphically that in the bridge arm two diodes are connected in series.

184
00:23:54,050 --> 00:23:58,810
Since the diode is rated for a max voltage of 600 volts.

185
00:23:59,350 --> 00:24:03,550
And our power supply has voltage over 1000 volts.

186
00:24:03,690 --> 00:24:07,410
So we should connect them in two pieces.

187
00:24:07,870 --> 00:24:11,990
Of course you can find diodes of other brands here too.

188
00:24:12,050 --> 00:24:14,010
But they have to be fast.

189
00:24:15,710 --> 00:24:24,490
Now we can also examine the system of the power output filter.

190
00:24:25,670 --> 00:24:38,350
After the diode bridge we have connected non-polar capacitors of rating 4.8 µF in series at 630 volts.

191
00:24:38,570 --> 00:24:40,950
These are film capacitors.

192
00:24:41,950 --> 00:24:49,290
And after them is the choke on output plus and on minus.

193
00:24:49,350 --> 00:24:52,230
Further, the same non-polar capacitors.

194
00:24:53,230 --> 00:25:01,950
And parallel to them, a small filter capacitor of 0.15 µF at 2000 volts.

195
00:25:02,650 --> 00:25:04,970
In iron this looks like this.

196
00:25:06,830 --> 00:25:10,130
Here are the first two capacitors.

197
00:25:10,970 --> 00:25:13,290
Then the output of the choke.

198
00:25:14,890 --> 00:25:16,690
And the next two capacitors.

199
00:25:16,790 --> 00:25:19,750
Here it's parallel — the 2 kV capacitor.

200
00:25:20,030 --> 00:25:22,570
And we have output plus and minus.

201
00:25:23,410 --> 00:25:30,050
Such a system let us deliver a quality signal from the power supply.

202
00:25:30,050 --> 00:25:37,710
And during work even on big loads, the ripples there make up 1.5-2 volts.

203
00:25:38,170 --> 00:25:41,830
At a load voltage of 200 volts.

204
00:25:42,450 --> 00:25:50,030
That is, the oscillogram comes out quite clean, if observing through a device.

205
00:25:51,650 --> 00:26:02,270
And plus, these chokes are also responsible for the correct work of the voltage protection.

206
00:26:02,730 --> 00:26:07,350
That is, regardless of what we connect here at the output, what devices.

207
00:26:08,410 --> 00:26:13,030
You know this block at me will work in specific devices.

208
00:26:14,270 --> 00:26:21,190
Connected with big high frequencies, static potentials.

209
00:26:22,210 --> 00:26:25,750
All connected with our specific work form.

210
00:26:26,010 --> 00:26:31,390
And so we should protect these chains from influence at the output.

211
00:26:32,290 --> 00:26:38,270
The choke here consists of 10 turns, of millimeter wire.

212
00:26:40,770 --> 00:26:44,190
Ring dimensions used are shown.

213
00:26:44,450 --> 00:26:49,210
And here I indicated that two rings are used in each choke.

214
00:26:50,030 --> 00:26:51,190
Here they are, these rings.

215
00:26:51,270 --> 00:26:53,590
Physically I stacked them one on top of another.

216
00:26:53,830 --> 00:26:55,690
A kind of barrel came out.

217
00:26:56,430 --> 00:26:59,450
And I bound it with masking tape.

218
00:27:00,390 --> 00:27:05,770
After which PVC-insulated wire was wound.

219
00:27:05,770 --> 00:27:08,250
Here they are, these chokes.

220
00:27:08,730 --> 00:27:14,550
And also they're wrapped around with fluoroplastic additional insulation.

221
00:27:15,050 --> 00:27:19,270
Overall, I explained the main nuances on the schematic diagram.

222
00:27:20,310 --> 00:27:25,690
Dimensions of the power pulse transformer's core are also indicated.

223
00:27:26,370 --> 00:27:33,090
You can use ferrite of smaller dimensions and other brands, other permeabilities.

224
00:27:33,090 --> 00:27:34,370
This isn't principal.

225
00:27:34,790 --> 00:27:41,150
Only the clock generator frequency will change under each ferrite.

226
00:27:41,270 --> 00:27:42,230
You'll need to pick it.

227
00:27:42,290 --> 00:27:49,030
I showed the principle in previous videos on the lab power supply.

228
00:27:50,030 --> 00:27:52,650
Now a few more nuances in iron.

229
00:27:52,950 --> 00:27:57,970
Here if you assemble it the same as I did — the power module.

230
00:27:58,610 --> 00:28:00,910
And the control board located above it.

231
00:28:00,910 --> 00:28:13,970
Then in such a build the wires going from the switches to the primary winding will inevitably pass under the board and the master chip.

232
00:28:14,710 --> 00:28:22,770
In this case under the whole board area you must make a screen of aluminum foil.

233
00:28:23,530 --> 00:28:29,210
In this case I glued the foil to cardboard on the back side.

234
00:28:29,210 --> 00:28:38,210
This will prevent pickups from the primary winding onto the master UC3825N chip.

235
00:28:38,990 --> 00:28:46,130
Pickups happen on pins 6 and 7 where the frequency-setting capacitor is located.

236
00:28:48,210 --> 00:28:50,610
One more condition.

237
00:28:50,810 --> 00:29:05,330
If you have such a scheme with galvanically isolated independent power supplies, then the aluminum screen isn't connected to the common minus of the master chip.

238
00:29:07,350 --> 00:29:31,470
Further, you should make sure there's no accidental contact between open metal surfaces and power parts through which the input power and output pass.

239
00:29:31,470 --> 00:29:40,270
For this we should also make a dielectric gasket.

240
00:29:40,510 --> 00:29:53,570
I made it from molded plastic, this way preventing accidental contact.

241
00:29:54,970 --> 00:30:00,310
In this case it's all located here.

242
00:30:01,690 --> 00:30:03,850
On this video we finish.

243
00:30:04,210 --> 00:30:05,970
Now we'll move to assembly.

244
00:30:08,390 --> 00:30:22,990
All the best everyone, successful experiments — and the next video on this system will already be about how I test it under load, on the output oscillogram, about the regulation possibilities.
